\begin_layout Frame

\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout FrameTitle
Deriving the HeckMaC LS Equation
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Frame
Assuming a HeckMaC separable utility function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U\left(c_{t},h_{t}\right)=c_{t}^{\delta_{1}}-\gamma_{2}h_{t}^{\delta_{2}}
\]

\end_inset

 and taking logarithms of the FOC, we can define the ISE
\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ln h_{t}=\Big[\frac{\ln\lambda_{t}-\ln\gamma_{2}-\ln\delta_{2}}{\delta_{2}-1}\Big]+\frac{t}{\delta_{2}-1}\ln\Big(\frac{1+\rho}{1+r_{t}}\Big)+\underbrace{\frac{1}{\delta_{2}-1}}_{\equiv\delta\text{ (ISE)}}\ln w_{t}\label{key}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
pause
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
How do we take first differences to eliminate 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{t}$
\end_inset

?
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
pause
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
By definition:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{t+1}=E_{t}[\lambda_{t+1}]+\epsilon_{t+1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Assuming rational expectation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{t+1}$
\end_inset

 is orthogonal to information available at 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
pause
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame

\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout FrameTitle
HeckMaC Estimation with Uncertainty
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{1+\rho}{1+r_{t}}\lambda_{t} & = & E_{t}[\lambda_{t+1}]\\
 & = & \lambda_{t+1}-\epsilon_{t+1}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
pause
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\lambda_{t}$
\end_inset

 obtained taking logs and using Taylor expansion around 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{t+1}=0$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\ln\lambda_{t}+\ln\Big(\frac{1+r_{t}}{1+\rho}\Big) & =\ln\left(\lambda_{t+1}-\epsilon_{t+1}\right)-\ln\lambda_{t+1}+\ln\lambda_{t+1}\\
 & \approx\ln\lambda_{t+1}+\underset{\equiv u_{t}}{\underbrace{\frac{1}{\lambda_{t+1}}\left(-\epsilon_{t+1}\right)}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Frame

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame

\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout FrameTitle
Consistency of ISE estimates I
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Frame
Taking first differences we get rid of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{t}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
pause
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta\ln h_{it}=\gamma+\mu_{i}+\delta\Delta\ln w_{it}+\delta\Delta u_{it}+e_{it}\label{key}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
BUT we still have the term 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{it}$
\end_inset

 after differencing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
To get a consistent estimator of the ISE 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=\frac{1}{\delta_{2}-1}$
\end_inset

 , need 
\begin_inset Formula $cov(u_{it},\ln{w_{it}})=0$
\end_inset

 for all individuals.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
pause
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Altonji (1986): reasonable if individuals know wages one period in advance
 and have rational expectation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{t+1}$
\end_inset

 is orthogonal to information in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, so uncorrelated with time-
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 variables like 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln{w_{it}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame

\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout FrameTitle
Consistency of ISE estimates II
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
cov(u_{it},\ln{w_{t}}) & = & E_{t}(u_{it}\ln{w_{t}})-E_{t}(u_{it})E_{t}(\ln{w_{it}})\\
 & = & E_{t}\Big(\frac{(1+r_{t})\epsilon_{it+1}}{(1+\rho)\lambda_{t}}\ln{w_{it}}\Big)\\
 & = & \frac{1+r_{t}}{(1+\rho)\lambda_{t}}E_{t}(\epsilon_{it+1}\ln{w_{it}})\\
 & = & 0
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
pause
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
First line uses definition of covariance, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Second line uses definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{it}$
\end_inset

 and the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{t}(u_{it})=\frac{1+r_{t}}{(1+\rho)\lambda_{t}}E_{t}(\epsilon_{it+1})$
\end_inset

 , 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Third line uses the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a constant in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Last line from RE: orthogonality of error terms
\end_layout

\end_deeper
